Record of Agarest War is a great tactics JRPG. Sadly, it is horrid on an Android... They did not do a very good job porting it over, as the touch screen controls are lazy and unimaginative. When navigating an exploration area, for example (a common feature used throughout the game, which is oftentimes mandatory if you want to progress the story), after heading down a branching path, you may find yourself unable to go back the way you came, simply because the game isn't registering your touch on the bottom-right hand corner of the screen. The window for it is far too narrow. This is a huge oversight, as it can hinder progress and stop you from wanting to loot the area's chests.  If they had only applied a more user-friendly control system, this port would be phenomenal. As a fan of the game was excited to replay this wonderful game on the go, for no less than $17 after tax, I am extremely disappointed this wasn't handled better.  So take note, fellow gamers: Record of Agarest War is awesome. But you should avoid this version like the plague. Get a used PS3 or Xbox 360/Xbone, and buy it on there. It's worth a playthrough. Just not on your phone.

replyContent: Maybe you did not notice the "full touch mode" ? It is available from the Option screen (along with different configuration for the controls), with the possibility to have an help icon (that you can disable) teaching you where you can touch the menus and controls. In general A button is validation and B cancel , while C and D are contextual .

content: Good game play and dialog
Epic game is epic.

I like the game.  I'm hooked.  It's the closest thing I've found to Final Fantasy Tactics, which (to be completely honest) is the game I really want.  The combat system is intriguing and keeps it interesting, but the cut scenes are a drag.  You can either fast-forward through them and therefore have no idea what the possible repercussions will be when you have to make a choice, or you wait for them to talk... in Japanese only, of course.  Can you add an option to just instantly pop up the text and turn off the spoken audio?  Or could the installation of japanese voice have been optional?  (1.8GB is huge!!!)  The game would also benefit greatly if there were a built-in wiki/encyclopedia/game guide that showed more about the stuff you've done, or where you can get some specific material for alchemy crafting or things like that.  There is a surprisingly long list of IAPs for a purchased game.  Many of them are obviously optional (like buying extra points that you would otherwise earn with sufficient grinding), but it's hard to tell if certain items can only be obtained by purchasing them.
Need more quality games like this.

replyContent: GooglePlay does install the 1.8 GB OBB file in the shared storage  exactly as listed in the game description, usually 99% of devices DO report their SDcard as the shared storage aka "external" except a few Samsung devices which report their internal memory as being the external one. We welcome any suggestion how to fix this Samsung bug.

ok... for your information Samsung has an SD card storage NAD external SD card. the regular SD card which most others just use is an external card. replyContent:
Thank you for your comment but for your information 99% of the game is already stored in your "shared storage" since 1.8GB is a GooglePlay OBB file installed per their standards in the /Android/obb//  :

http://developer.android.com/google/play/expansion-files.html#StorageLocation
